SIMPLE: impregnation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impregnation
<hw>Im`preg*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>impr⟦eacute⟧gnation</ets>, LL. <ets>impraegnatio</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of impregnating or the state of being
impregnated; fecundation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The fusion of a female germ cell
(ovum) with a male germ cell (in animals, a spermatozo⟦oum⟧n) to form a
single new cell endowed with the power of developing into a new
individual; fertilization; fecundation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the broadest biological sense, impregnation, or
sexual generation, consists simply in the coalescence of two similar
masses of protoplasmic matter, either derived from different parts of
the same organism or from two distinct organisms. From the single mass,
which results from the fusion, or coalescence, of these two masses, a
new organism develops.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That with which anything is impregnated.</def>
<rj><au>Derham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Intimate mixture; infusion; saturation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>An ore deposit, with indefinite
boundaries, consisting of rock impregnated with ore.</def>
<rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imprejudicate</ent>⟦br⟧
